reviews.text: Lovely library with all the amenities I appreciate. Air conditioning, charging stations, plenty of seating and computers as well as a great selection of books, scanner, printer, and copying machine. Staff is very friendly and helpful as well.

this is the top library on the island of Maui!  manga comix, science and computer books, Hawaiiana you name it!  before it tragically closed almost two years ago I would visit it 4-5 times a week.  the good news is looking forward to all the new titles they will have added in the last two years!

The Kahului Library is awesome. They have an excellent selection of magazines and newspapers, plenty of computers to use, and a great selection of books. The Hawaiiana section is filled with tons of books containing legends, culture, stories, art, cooking, and everything else Hawai'i. The fiction section is also filled with many popular books from many well known authors. They also have a great reference stuff here with many cool atlases and large books to flip through. I am a bit of a library nerd and I really enjoy Hawaii's public library system. The app is awesome and has made my life so much easier to remember when to return or to request a book anytime. I spend tons of time at the library and this location does not disappoint.

The staff is really friendly and helpful. There's parking and it's centrally located. The A/C has been broken for a while so the hours were cut short... but I think it will be repaired soon. The library in Kihei is bigger with a nicer looking facility.
Good customer service. Good selection of books. Can order from other libraries in the state. Nice people.

reviews.text:

Excellent place to study on campus, this library has A/C and many places to get work done in quiet and study-friendly locations. This is a really large library as well with a large selection of books and esoteric magazines that are generally cost-prohibitive to the majority of the public. I think the magazine selection is a big part of what makes this library special, but there are a lot of other characteristics specific to this library that make it special.

The University of Hawaii at Manoa's Hamilton Library is the largest research library in the state of Hawaii. It is located on the campus of the University of Hawaii at Manoa. The Library is an important resource for all of the University of Hawaii system campuses, including the flagship Manoa campus, which is an institution that receives federal funding for land, sea, and space grants.

A quiet and respectful place with an abundance of books for studies.

The librarian I talked with was extremely helpful and knowledgeable. There are multiple floors with a whole lot of shelves crammed with books, and several spots to study. Some outlets here and there. WiFi is for UH, so bring  a hotspot phone or such if you need network.

Public parking nearby for a $2 a half hour (woah). There's a parking structure on Dole for $5 (about a 10 minute walk) or you can try to scrap a free parking spot along Dole street.

Relative to the other buildings on campus Hamilton library has always been well maintained and clean all the times I have visited there (at least a few times a week for two years). The only downsides are no food or drinks (besides water) are allowed inside, but if you're sneaky you may be able to eat a quiet snack like mochi or something. The security gaurds walk around regularly but are friendly and the size and amount of areas to  find a nice quiet spot to study or get lost in books is way better than sinclair in my opinion.

reviews.text:
This is a very well-run and highly respected medical center with very well-run operations and the highest quality physicians. This is also a world renowned and nationally ranked Healthcare organization that is trusted by locals and people that actually work in the healthcare industry. If you value your health and the health of your family make the small but critical investment of driving to this healrhcare facility and establishing care here.

There are many other very dangerous hospitals on the island that should be avoided at all costs. The for-profit healthcare industry in America in general has a lot of problems with its infastructure and unfortunately in general, it actually causes a lot of disease in patients; and sometimes just treating symptoms instead if any underlying pathology, which can be financially lucrative for the hospital. There are many articles detailing this unfortunate reality.

In a healthcare landscape riddled with questionable integrity it's important to find healthcare professionals and organizations that are trustworthy because your health is so incredibly valuable. In general Queens has that, especially when considering other more poorly run hospitals in the area with high rates of bad outcomes and serious injuries. Make sure you ask your doctor a lot of questions and do your own research and most importantly make good health decisions, starting with the hospital and physician you choose.

When Jan (library staff) first answered the phone she was so very helpful in assisting me w/my forgotten library card PIN #. She went above and beyond the call of duty in answering all of my questions and reserving a computer spot for me which I had to call two times to change it due to the delays the bus transit system was experiencing that day. And, when I arrived feeling exasperated due to bus delays, I asked for Jan and a very nice female library staff said she had stepped away and asked how she could help me. Due to my late arrival beyond my control, she immediately directed me to an available computer or laptop to use. Since it was my first time visiting this branch, I had no clue that printing was free of charge unless library patrons donated upwards of fifteen cents per page printed. Of course I had no problems donating a dollar for 9 pages! I can't imagine any of our wonderful public libraries going w/out the necessary supplies it needs to serve the public with! I happen to have a special fondness for libraries. As a kid all I ever wanted to do was read every single book in our village's local library! So, MAHALO to Jan and her co-workers who went the extra mile for me b/c my feet couldn't take any extra mileage W/ALL the walking I ended up doing due to bus delays! And, that's a story for another time. Aloha!!!

reviews.text: The mission of the Law Library at the University of Hawaii's William S. Richardson School of Law is to support the research, publishing, educational, and service initiatives of the law school's professors, students, and staff. This mission is accomplished by the Law Library through the collection, organization, dissemination, preservation, and preservation of legal and law-related information in all available formats, through the provision of the highest quality service, support, and instructional programs, and through the creation of a physical environment that is conducive to user needs.

reviews.text:
Its a good place to study; nice, cold, and quiet. Large enough spaces and rooms to have study groups in, plenty of outlets, good printers and computers with allot of software. BUT they don't tend to be super accurate when it comes to open hours. So far as being a 3rd year I haven't had that issue but the hours do change allot without notice so you have to check before you to be sure.

However, during finals time they are very consistent with the hours and the longest they were open was until 2 am. The longest I ever stayed was 1 am.

All-in-all good place to study between classes but double check if they are open for the evenings.

It's a great learning space but HPU doesn't take full advantage of it or manage its availability well. Hours seem to be shortened without being updated. There have been several times when I've arrived when it was supposed to be open to find out that the hours had changed and had to wait around until it opened up.

However, the most annoying part of LC is that it always closes at 10PM, except Friday and Saturday when it closes at 6pm, but other universities such as UH have facilities that stay open much later. To add insult to injury, as you leave the LC after it closes you have to walk past the new HPU 'E-Sports Arena' with is nice new computers, comfy gaming chairs and see that it's open until 11PM almost everyday of the week.

I love my video games and I understand the upcoming world of E-sports and it's potential future impacts. However, this is purportedly an academic institution not Dave and Busters. Is it too much to ask to have similar study hall hours to that of UH which keeps facilities open for students who want to study late? Or will the priorities of HPU continue to lie with profiting off of students while claiming to have their best academic interests at heart.

reviews.text: I personally am a big fan of Hawaii library system. Since I live on this island, it's a challenge to get a chance to read good books and resources for my personal research and reading. Even the amount of book is not huge and the kind of book is not much various, they still provide a good service to keep reading and approaching books. I often go to the library with my daughter, and Hilo library presents a really good environment to read a book. To enter the library, you need to present the vaccination card and ID card.

This library is AMAZING! The courtyard, the staff, the selection of books, the ability to order books from ANY library in Hawai'i and have them shipped. AND, if you're only staying in the area for a short time you can purchase a three-month membership for an extremely reasonable price. I love this library so much and would live here if I could.

I love libraries but Limited opening hours and their system will charge you fees if you don't pick up a reserved book in a certain time frame. Like settle down or have better hours. No need to be angry every time I loan a book. Less of a library and more of a book prison.

I'm just a tourist, but if you want a quiet place to read, this is it. The open courtyard area is SO pleasant! I was able to read undisturbed for over 3 hours! I can't say much about anything else since I don't have a library card here, but man is it a great environment to relax and read in.
Very serene and peaceful library. Love the courtyard, garden, open air reading and working spaces🌿so pleasant, the courtyard is an unexpected treasure🌺

reviews.text: Awesome service! Help desk helped me right away when I had questions to ask. I  Was able to reload my student ID card with funds to print my reading for my bus 240 class quickly, easy to use computers and print station log in stations everytime I go its usually easy and simple unless I have issues reloading my card like previous times but I end up getting my printing done right away. Thanks a lot for your helpful ways and simple easy printing. Also, for direction on how to get around campus this is my first year as a transfer student here at UH Hilo so I tend to get lost often but end up finding my way by asking for directions or following a paper map of campus.
